SIMPLE: sphenoid
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Sphenoid
<hw>Sphe"noid</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <?/<?/<?/;
<grk>sfh`n</grk> a wedge + <grk>e'i^dos</grk> form: cf. F.
<ets>sph⟦eacute⟧no⟦ium⟧de</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Wedge-shaped;
<as>as, a <ex>sphenoid</ex> crystal</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>Of or pertaining to the sphenoid
bone.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Sphenoid bone</b></col> <fld>(Anat.)</fld>, <cd>an
irregularly shaped bone in front of the occipital in the base of the
skull of the higher vertebrates. It is composed of several fetal bones
which become united the adult. See <er>Alisphenoid</er>,
<er>Basisphenoid</er>, <er>Orbitosphenoid</er>,
<er>Presphenoid</er>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sphenoid</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Sphenoid
<hw>Sphe"noid</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn>
<fld>(Crystallog.)</fld> <def>A wedge-shaped crystal bounded by four
equal isosceles triangles. It is the hemihedral form of a square
pyramid.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>The sphenoid bone.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sphenoidal</ent>⟦br⟧
